      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A fixed-rate mortgage keeps your monthly payment exactly the same for the life of the loan, while an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) starts with a lower rate that can change after an initial period. If you have a 5-year window on an ARM, the rate—and therefore your monthly payment—will adjust based on market rates at the end of that period, potentially increasing significantly if rates rise. For example, if rates jump by 1%, your payment could increase by roughly 8% to 10% depending on the specific ARM structure. You should carefully consider whether you plan to stay in the home for more than five years before committing to an ARM.",
